The circle is tangent to $\overline{AM}$ and $\overline{PM}$, so $O$ is the incenter of $\triangle APM$. Let $s$ be the semiperimeter of $\triangle APM$. Then $s = \frac{152}{2} = 76$.

[asy]
pair A,P,M,O;
A = (0,0);
P = (152,0);
M = (0,152);
O = (0,38);
draw(A--P--M--cycle);
draw(circle(O,19));
label("$A$",A,SW);
label("$P$",P,SE);
label("$M$",M,N);
label("$O$",O,W);
label("$19$",O--(O+19),N);
label("$19$",O--(O-19),S);
[/asy]

Since $O$ is the incenter, $AO = OM = 19$. Therefore, $AP = AO + OP = 19 + OP$ and $AM = AO + OM = 19 + 19 = 38$.

The area of $\triangle APM$ is $\frac{1}{2} \cdot AP \cdot AM = \frac{1}{2} \cdot (19 + OP) \cdot 38$.

The semiperimeter of $\triangle APM$ is $s = \frac{1}{2} (AP + PM + AM) = \frac{1}{2} (19 + OP + PM + 38) = 76$.

The inradius of $\triangle APM$ is $r = \frac{\text{area}}{s} = \frac{\frac{1}{2} \cdot (19 + OP) \cdot 38}{76} = \frac{19 + OP}{4}$.

Since $r = 19$, we have $\frac{19 + OP}{4} = 19$, so $19 + OP = 76$, and $OP = \boxed{57}$.

